.sample-grid {
  /* Explicit height so AG Grid's internal height:100% resolves to a real
     value. A pure flex/100% chain collapses to 0 here because the host's
     height is auto. Matches the editor grids (item-depth/customer-aggrid). */
  display: block;
  width: 100%;
  height: calc(100vh - 200px);
  min-height: 400px;
}

content.text:
`npx tsc --noEmit` exited cleanly (no output, exit 0). CSS-only change, so no TS impact was expected.

## Report

### Root cause
`.sample-tracking` uses `height: 100%`, which resolves only if the router-outlet host above it has a resolved height. The grid element `.sample-grid` was sized purely with `flex: 1 1 auto` + `min-height: 400px`. AG Grid sets its internal `.ag-root-wrapper` / `.ag-body-viewport` to `height: 100%`, and that percentage resolves against the host element's *content* height. Because the flex/`100%` chain never bottoms out at a concrete pixel height, the host resolved to ~0px and AG Grid's inner `height:100%` collapsed to 0 (the `min-height` applies to the outer element box but is not inherited by AG Grid's percentage-height inner viewport — hence rows in the DOM but `.ag-body-viewport` = 0px, `.ag-root-wrapper` ~2px borders). The working editor grids (`item-depth-aggrid`, `customer-aggrid`) avoid this by giving the grid an explicit `calc(100vh - Npx)` height that does not depend on the parent chain.

### Fix (only file edited)
`src/app/pages/sample_tracking/sample_tracking.component.scss`

Before:
```scss
.sample-grid {
  flex: 1 1 auto;
  width: 100%;
  min-height: 400px;
}
```

After:
```scss
.sample-grid {
  /* Explicit height so AG Grid's internal height:100% resolves to a real
     value. A pure flex/100% chain collapses to 0 here because the host's
     height is auto. Matches the editor grids (item-depth/customer-aggrid). */
  display: block;
  width: 100%;
  height: calc(100vh - 200px);
  min-height: 400px;
}
```

The `<ag-grid-angular class="... sample-grid">` element now has a concrete viewport-relative height, so AG Grid's `height:100%` inner elements resolve correctly. No HTML change was needed — the class is already applied to the grid element, and putting the calc directly on it keeps the fix self-contained (no extra wrapper required). No AG Grid modules touched.

### tsc result
`npx tsc --noEmit` → exit 0, no errors.

### Risk / caveats
- I used `calc(100vh - 200px)`, the same offset as `item-depth-aggrid`. The Sample Tracking page has a different chrome (single `mat-toolbar` ~64px plus the global app header) than the editor pages, so the exact 200px may leave slightly more/less bottom gap than ideal. It will render at a correct, non-zero height regardless; only fine vertical fit might differ by a few px. If pixel-perfect fit matters, the offset can be tuned after a visual check (I can't run the browser).
- The fix is `vh`-based, so it is independent of any parent element I don't own — no reliance on untouchable parents. `min-height: 400px` is kept as a floor for very short viewports.
